And he said to them all, If any man will come after me, let him deny himself, and take up his cross daily, and follow me. }{\cs25\fs16\lang0\langfe1033\langnp0\insrsid15167464\charrsid15167464 24}{\insrsid15167464 
 For whosoever will save his life shall lose it: but whosoever will lose his life for my sake, the same shall save it. }{\cs25\fs16\lang0\langfe1033\langnp0\insrsid15167464\charrsid15167464 25}{\insrsid15167464  For what i
s a man advantaged, if he gain the whole world, and lose himself, or be cast away? }{\cs25\fs16\lang0\langfe1033\langnp0\insrsid15167464\charrsid15167464 26}{\insrsid15167464 
 For whosoever shall be ashamed of me and of my words, of him shall the Son of man be ashamed, when he shall come in his own glory, and in his Father's, and of the holy angels. }{\cs25\fs16\lang0\langfe1033\langnp0\insrsid15167464\charrsid15167464 27}{
\insrsid15167464  }{\insrsid15167464\charrsid8408440 But}{\insrsid15167464  I tell you of a truth, there be some standing here, which shall not taste of death, till they see the kingdom of God.
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2974322 \fs24\lang1033\langfe255\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af34\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp255 {\cs27\b\f1\ul\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\insrsid15167464 
\par }\pard\plain \s28\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2453661 \fs28\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs25\insrsid875216 
\par }{\cs27\b\f1\ul\insrsid13635561\charrsid15167464 Luke 9:23-27}{\insrsid13635561  And he said to them all, If any man will come after me, let him deny himself, and take up his cross daily, and follow me.
\par 
\par }{\cs25\insrsid11501331 It}{\cs25\insrsid13635561  is interesting how one little word can really strengthen a thought. In this verse, the word }{\cs25\i\insrsid13635561\charrsid13635561 DAILY}{\cs25\insrsid13635561 
 stands out brightly as a challenge and a reminder. I have spoken many times about how the scripture can be used as a sort of mnemonic device (something which helps us remember the right way to think, act and live).  It would be good to check ourselves }{
\cs25\i\insrsid13635561\charrsid11501331 DAILY}{\cs25\insrsid13635561 : are we taking up our cross, or are we just going through our daily routine without thought, effort or purpose? Indeed, it would be good at least }{
\cs25\i\insrsid13635561\charrsid13635561 hourly}{\cs25\insrsid13635561  to check on how we are bearing our cross this }{\cs25\i\insrsid13635561\charrsid11501331 day}{\cs25\insrsid13635561 , if indeed we are struggling at all. }{
\cs25\insrsid13635561\charrsid13635561 
\par }{\cs25\insrsid13635561 
\par }{\cs25\insrsid11501331 A similar reading from St Mark is used on the 3}{\cs25\super\insrsid11501331\charrsid11501331 rd}{\cs25\insrsid11501331  Sunday of Great Lent }{\cs25\f1\fs16\lang0\langfe1033\langnp0\insrsid11501331\charrsid11501331 (Mark 8:34-9:1)
}{\cs25\insrsid11501331 . }{\cs25\insrsid13635561 
\par }{\cs25\insrsid11501331 
\par One cannot understand what the Lord is saying unless he understands what he should }{\cs25\i\insrsid11501331\charrsid2453661 deny}{\cs25\insrsid11501331  for himself, and what the }{\cs25\i\insrsid11501331\charrsid2453661 talking up of the cross}{
\cs25\insrsid11501331  means. This cannot be understood unless there is effort in the Christian life. 
\par There have been many false interpretations of our Lord\rquote s command. Various heresies have taught that we must deny ourselves all pleasure or even cause ourselves pain and suffering (since, in taking up }{\cs25\i\insrsid11501331\charrsid11501331 our}{
\cs25\insrsid11501331  cross, we must suffer as our Lord did on }{\cs25\i\insrsid11501331\charrsid11501331 His}{\cs25\insrsid11501331  cross) in order to be saved. Many have left the Lord\rquote 
s company, like those who heard His teaching about being the bread of life, because this command seemed incomprehensible and too difficult for them. 
\par }{\cs25\insrsid2453661 
\par }\pard \s28\qj \li720\ri720\widctlpar\faauto\rin720\lin720\itap0\pararsid2453661 {\cs25\insrsid2453661 \'93}{\cs25\insrsid2453661\charrsid2453661 Many therefore of his disciples, when they had heard this, said, This is an hard saying; who can hear it?  }{
\cs25\insrsid2453661 \'85}{\cs25\insrsid2453661\charrsid2453661  }{\cs25\f1\fs16\insrsid2453661\charrsid2453661 66}{\cs25\insrsid2453661\charrsid2453661  From that time many of his disciples went back, and walked no more with him.}{\cs25\insrsid2453661 
\'94 }{\cs25\f1\fs16\insrsid2453661\charrsid2453661 John 6:60.66}{\cs25\insrsid2453661\charrsid2453661   
\par }\pard \s28\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2453661 {\cs25\insrsid11501331 
\par }{\cs25\insrsid4674283 All of the commands of our Lord can be understood only if they are followed. This is 
partially counter-intuitive to the mind of man. We tend to do something only after we have investigated it, and understood at least a little about it. }{\cs25\insrsid16454759 At first, one must struggle to deny }{\cs25\insrsid4483046 oneself pleasurable}{
\cs25\insrsid16454759  things, such as }{\cs25\insrsid4483046 indulgence}{\cs25\insrsid16454759  of the flesh, luxury and ease, but as one grows in the Christian life, he sees that the things which }{\cs25\insrsid4483046 previously}{\cs25\insrsid16454759 
 were difficult to deny }{\cs25\insrsid4483046 to himself change in their appearance, and he sees them as they really are. 
\par 
\par }\pard \s28\qj \li720\ri720\widctlpar\faauto\rin720\lin720\itap0\pararsid4483046 {\cs25\insrsid4483046\charrsid4483046 There is a way which seemeth right unto a man, but the end thereof are the ways of death.}{\cs25\insrsid4483046  }{
\cs25\f1\fs16\insrsid4483046\charrsid4483046 (Pro}{\cs25\f1\fs16\lang0\langfe1033\langnp0\insrsid4483046\charrsid4483046 verbs}{\cs25\f1\fs16\insrsid4483046\charrsid4483046  14:12)}{\cs25\insrsid4483046 
\par }\pard \s28\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2453661 {\cs25\insrsid4483046\charrsid4483046 
\par }{\cs25\insrsid4483046 A life of indulgence, luxury and ease does not bring happiness, and never has and never will. It only wastes time, and dulls the senses of the soul, and we are left with a vague feeling of unhappiness and unfulfil
lment. The things we are called to deny ourselves of are all injurious to us.  We are able to see this only with experience. Most people never know why they feel this way. A very few, such as the prodigal son, come to their senses and see why their soul i
s in such a state. A better way to learn the benefit of denying ourselves is to live with effort and desire.  }{\cs25\insrsid16454759 
\par }{\cs25\insrsid11501331 
